  "prompt": "What is the transpose of a matrix ?",
  "response": "The **transpose of a matrix** is a fundamental operation in linear algebra that flips a matrix over its diagonal. This effectively switches the row and column indices of each element in the matrix.\n\n## Definition\n\nGiven a matrix \\( A \\) with dimensions \\( m \\times n \\) (i.e., \\( m \\) rows and \\( n \\) columns), the **transpose** of \\( A \\), denoted as \\( A^\\top \\) or \\( A^T \\), is an \\( n \\times m \\) matrix where the rows of \\( A \\) become the columns of \\( A^\\top \\), and the columns of \\( A \\) become the rows of \\( A^\\top \\).\n\nMathematically, if\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\na_{11} & a_{12} & \\dots & a_{1n} \\\\\na_{21} & a_{22} & \\dots & a_{2n} \\\\\n\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\na_{m1} & a_{m2} & \\dots & a_{mn} \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix},\n\\]\nthen\n\\[\nA^\\top = \\begin{bmatrix}\na_{11} & a_{21} & \\dots & a_{m1} \\\\\na_{12} & a_{22} & \\dots & a_{m2} \\\\\n\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\na_{1n} & a_{2n} & \\dots & a_{mn} \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}.\n\\]\n\n## Example\n\nConsider the matrix\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 2 & 3 \\\\\n4 & 5 & 6 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\nwhich is a \\( 2 \\times 3 \\) matrix (2 rows and 3 columns).\n\nThe transpose of \\( A \\) is\n\\[\nA^\\top = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 4 \\\\\n2 & 5 \\\\\n3 & 6 \\\\\n\\end{bmatrix},\n\\]\na \\( 3 \\times 2 \\) matrix.\n\n## Properties of Transpose\n\n1. **Double Transpose**: Taking the transpose twice returns the original matrix:\n   \\[\n   (A^\\top)^\\top = A\n   \\]\n\n2. **Addition**: The transpose of a sum is the sum of the transposes:\n   \\[\n   (A + B)^\\top = A^\\top + B^\\top\n   \\]\n   where \\( A \\) and \\( B \\) are matrices of the same dimensions.\n\n3. **Scalar Multiplication**: The transpose of a scalar multiple is the scalar multiple of the transpose:\n   \\[\n   (cA)^\\top = cA^\\top\n   \\]\n   where \\( c \\) is a scalar.\n\n4. **Product of Matrices**: The transpose of a product of two matrices is the product of their transposes in reverse order:\n   \\[\n   (AB)^\\top = B^\\top A^\\top\n   \\]\n   provided the dimensions are compatible for multiplication.\n\n5. **Symmetric Matrix**: A matrix is called **symmetric** if it is equal to its transpose:\n   \\[\n   A = A^\\top\n   \\]\n\n## Applications\n\n- **Solving Systems of Equations**: Transposes are used in various methods for solving linear systems.\n  \n- **Orthogonality and Inner Products**: In defining orthogonal vectors and inner products, the transpose plays a key role.\n  \n- **Computer Graphics**: Transposes are used in transforming coordinates and manipulating geometric data.\n  \n- **Data Analysis**: In statistics and machine learning, transposing data matrices is common for operations like PCA (Principal Component Analysis).\n\nUnderstanding the transpose of a matrix is essential for deeper studies in linear algebra, including topics like matrix multiplication, eigenvalues, and vector spaces.",
